Mali detection fallback via GL_RENDERER.

Some libmali blobs (notably the ODROID/Amlogic variants shipped on
Amlogic-old devices) report a GL_VENDOR string that does not contain
"ARM", so gl4es misses setting hardext.vendor = VEND_ARM and therefore
skips the Mali-specific workarounds (fbomakecurrent, fbounbind) guarded
by that flag. As a fallback, also look at GL_RENDERER: if it contains
"Mali" we're on a Mali GPU regardless of what GL_VENDOR claims.

diff --git a/src/glx/hardext.c b/src/glx/hardext.c
--- a/src/glx/hardext.c
+++ b/src/glx/hardext.c
@@ -430,6 +430,14 @@ void GetHardwareExtensions(int notest)
         hardext.vendor = VEND_ARM;
     else if(strstr(vendor, "Imagination Technologies"))
         hardext.vendor = VEND_IMGTEC;
+    // Fallback: some libmali blobs don't put "ARM" in GL_VENDOR, so the
+    // Mali-specific workarounds further down (fbomakecurrent, fbounbind)
+    // would be skipped. GL_RENDERER on Mali always contains "Mali".
+    if(hardext.vendor != VEND_ARM) {
+        const char *renderer_probe = (const char *) gles_glGetString(GL_RENDERER);
+        if(renderer_probe && strstr(renderer_probe, "Mali"))
+            hardext.vendor = VEND_ARM;
+    }
     if(hardext.esversion>1) {
         if(testGLSL("#version 120", 1))
             hardext.glsl120 = 1;
